    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-08-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-08-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="257"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d257">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation, lot 64 D
                    199</note>
                <head>No. 257<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Deputy Director of the
                        Office of Western European Affairs (<persName>Tyler</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1954-08-18">August 18,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Visit of French Ambassador</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>The Secretary</item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName>Bonnet</persName>, French Ambassador</item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>William R. Tyler</persName>, <gloss target="#t_WE1"
                            >WE</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Ambassador <persName>Bonnet</persName> called on the Secretary at the latter’s
                    request.</p>
                <p>1. The Secretary told him that he hoped that the French Government would not
                    deviate from its present policy of non-recognition of Communist China and that
                    it would observe the moratorium during the forthcoming General Assembly session.
                    He added that rumors had come to our ears of a possible change in the French
                    position and that if these were true, we would consider it a serious matter.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador unhesitatingly replied that no change was contemplated by the
                    French Government. He had read the transcript of the conversation of
                        <persName>Mendes-France</persName> with <persName corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou
                        En-lai</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d257fn1">French Premier <persName>Pierre
                            Mendès-France</persName> had met with <persName corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou
                            En-lai</persName> at Bern, Switzerland, on June 23; regarding their
                        meeting, see Secto 517 and telegram 5035, both June 24, <ref
                            target="frus1952-54v16#pg_1233">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">xvi</hi>, pp.
                            1233</ref> and <ref target="frus1952-54v16#pg_1239">1239</ref>,
                        respectively.</note> and there had been no reference whatsoever to the
                    subject. The Ambassador was convinced that there was no secret agreement or
                    understanding between France and Communist China concerning recognition. Indeed,
                    he said, there were no conversations going on between the two countries on any
                    subject and France was maintaining the embargo on strategic materials.</p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion pertaining to Indochina and the proposed European
                    Defense Community.]</p>
            </div>
